South Africa’s retirement savings crisis was well documented long before COVID-19 emerged. The resultant lockdown and economic downturn have further exacerbated the already perilous savings environment. Even before COVID-19 Old Mutual established that less than 6% of employees can afford to retire comfortably. Now with rising fuel and food prices and experts forecasting that annual salary increases are likely be lower than inflation this year, disposable income will continue to be constrained, heaping further pressure household budgets. COVID-19 lockdowns have also put pressure on employers who have witnessed first-hand the increase in staff resignations as employees now place great emphasis on healthy working environments. Labelled the Great Resignation around the world, South Africa has also experienced the phenomenon with record numbers of employees seeking new employment or opting to work for themselves. Surprisingly, the Remchannel Salary and Wage Remuneration Survey found that 53% of employees cited bullying, toxic work environment and low career prospects as reasons for leaving as opposed to only 19% who stated that remuneration was the driving factor to their departure. In this context, employers must also consider creating a holistic work environment that emphasize employee well-being and wellness alongside profits. An important part of that enhanced offering includes helping employees to save for retirement by providing access to a retirement fund and educating staff on their short and long-term financial health. To help employers in providing a retirement savings vehicle for their employees’ commercial umbrella funds offer companies a viable option that offer a range of benefits and market-related outcomes